    "body": "### Problem\n\nThe netrw's documentation for [`netrw-cd`](https://neovim.io/doc/user/pi_netrw.html#netrw-cd) states in a very ambiguous manner that upon its invocation it's going to change Neovim's current directory to netrw's one. However, it does so only for the netrw's window and not all of the open windows as `:cd` would. But, this can be worked around using `:cd`: after pressing `cd` in the netrw window, just run `:cd %` and it will set the current directory for all the windows. Yet, there too is a weird bug: if you have `g:netrw_liststyle` set to `3`, i.e. the \"tree view\", you'd get an error, because netrw buffer in that case would have a trailing `NetrwTreeListing` path entry. This can be worked around using the filename modifier `:h` as follows: `:cd %:h`. In that case it will properly set the working directory for all windows. By the way the `g:netrw_keepdir` option doesn't fix it in any way.\n\nThis is some nightmare workflow\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n`nvim --clean`\n`:Lexplore` (or ':Vexplore' and then press `2C` to change the editing window to the initial window)\nenter some directory and press `cd`\n`:redir @a`\n`:pwd`\n`:redir END`\n`2CTRL-W_CTRL_W`\n`:redir @b`\n`:pwd`\n`:redir END`\n`\"ap\"bp`\n\nor just run this one-liner from your shell\n```sh\nnvim --clean -c ':exe \"normal :Lexplore\\<cr>-2ggcd:let @a=\\\"netrw \\\"\\<cr>:redir @A\\<cr>:pwd\\<cr>:redir END\\<cr>2\\<c-w>\\<c-w>:let @b=\\\"window2 \\\"\\<cr>:redir @B\\<cr>:pwd\\<cr>:redir END\\<cr>\\\"aPJ:put! _\\<cr>:put! _\\<cr>\\\"bPJ\"'\n```\n\n### Expected behavior\n\n`cd` in netrw should work the same way as `:cd`, i.e. set the current directory for all windows. Alternatively, introduce a new `lcd` mapping (equivalently to `:lcd`) which would set the current directory only for the active window, and make the `cd` mapping set it for all windows.\n\nAnd It's also expected for the `g:netrw_liststyle=3` to behave in the same manner as the other styles.\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\nv0.12.0 commit ef0386fe9a\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nyes, vim 9.1\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nArchLinux (WSL)\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nWindows Terminal\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm-256color\n\n### Installation\n\nAUR neovim-git",
